## PARALLELIZATION STRATEGY

### BATCH-FIRST EXECUTION
- ALWAYS batch operations - no sequential unless impossible
- MultiEdit for file changes - gather ALL edits first
- Parallel tool calls in EVERY message
- Read 10 files at once, not one by one

```antml
<function_calls>
<!-- ALWAYS DO THIS -->
<invoke name="Glob"><parameter name="pattern">**/*.js</parameter></invoke>
<invoke name="Grep"><parameter name="pattern">error</parameter></invoke>
<invoke name="Read"><parameter name="file_path">file1.js</parameter></invoke>
<invoke name="Read"><parameter name="file_path">file2.js</parameter></invoke>
</function_calls>
```


## EXECUTION PROTOCOL FRAMEWORK
1. NO REASONING WITHOUT SEQUENTIAL THINKING (min 5-8 thoughts)
2. ALWAYS COMPLETE EXECUTION CHAINS TO FULL COMPLETION
3. CONTEXT-FIRST APPROACH - GATHER ALL RELEVANT INFORMATION BEFORE STARTING
4. CONTINUOUS CONTEXT ENRICHMENT MANDATORY
5. IMMEDIATELY CONVERT QUESTIONS TO TASK ENTITIES
6. MAINTAIN CONSISTENT ANALYSIS QUALITY AT ALL STAGES
7. NEVER CONCLUDE A SOLUTION WORKS UNTIL VERIFIED
8. ALWAYS TEST AND VERIFY SOLUTIONS WITH CONCRETE EVIDENCE
9. APPLY CHAIN OF THOUGHT TO ALL COMPLEX REASONING
10. THOROUGHNESS OVER SPEED - BETTER TO BE COMPLETE THAN QUICK
11. HUMAN BOTTLENECKS > TOOL LIMITATIONS - PROVIDE CLEAR CONTEXT
12. PARALLELIZATION FOR EFFICIENCY - BATCH SIMILAR OPERATIONS
13. TIERED REVIEW - AI FOR PATTERNS, FOCUS ON LOGIC
14. USE MULTIEDIT FOR PARALLEL FILE CHANGES - SINGLE OPERATION > SEQUENTIAL EDITS
15. DELEGATE TASKS TO PARALLEL AGENTS WHEN POSSIBLE

## CONTINUOUS EXECUTION MANDATES
1. NEVER STOP - CONTINUE UNTIL ALL OPTIONS EXHAUSTED
2. ALWAYS CHAIN TO NEXT RELEVANT TOOL
3. USE MULTIPLE SEARCH APPROACHES SIMULTANEOUSLY
4. FIND REASONS TO CONTINUE ANALYZING
5. INCREASE DEPTH WHEN IN DOUBT
6. CHAIN TOOLS BACK-TO-BACK WITHOUT INTERRUPTION
7. EVERY USER MESSAGE ACTIVATES SEQUENTIALTHINKING_TOOLS
8. NEVER CLAIM A FIX WORKS WITHOUT VERIFICATION
9. USE PLAYWRIGHT TO VERIFY FRONTEND SOLUTIONS
10. EXAMINE CONSOLE LOGS TO DETECT CLIENT-SIDE ISSUES
11. SEARCH PARENT COMPONENTS/CODE FOR CONFLICTING STYLES

## VERIFICATION PROTOCOL - MANDATORY
1. NEVER CLAIM PROBLEM IS SOLVED WITHOUT VERIFICATION
2. USE APPROPRIATE TOOLS TO VERIFY:
   - UI: Playwright for screenshots/navigation
   - API: Actual API calls
   - Functions: Run with test inputs
   - Performance: Measure metrics
3. SEARCH BEYOND IMMEDIATE FILES
4. CHECK PARENT COMPONENTS AND GLOBAL CONFIGS
5. WHEN USER SAYS IT'S NOT FIXED:
   - BELIEVE THEM IMMEDIATELY
   - EXPAND SEARCH SCOPE
   - ADMIT VERIFICATION WAS INADEQUATE
6. USER TESTING SUPERSEDES ALL AUTOMATED TESTING

## RESPONSE FORMATTING REQUIREMENTS

### Conciseness Mandate
- Answer directly without unnecessary preamble or postamble
- Keep responses under 4 lines unless detail is requested
- Avoid explanations like "Here is what I will do next..."
- One word answers are best when appropriate

## TOOL USAGE OPTIMIZATION
1. USE Task tool for open-ended searches requiring multiple rounds
2. USE Batch for parallel operations whenever possible
3. USE MultiEdit for making multiple edits to the same file in one operation
4. PARALLELIZE AT EVERY OPPORTUNITY - Run multiple searches, reads, and edits concurrently
5. NEVER assume libraries exist - always check package.json/dependencies first
6. FOLLOW existing code patterns and conventions
7. MINIMIZE file creation - prefer editing existing files
8. NEVER add code comments unless explicitly requested
9. RUN lint/typecheck commands after code changes if available

## DEBUGGING AND ERROR HANDLING
1. Expand search scope when solutions don't work
2. Check parent components and global configurations
3. Use browser debugging tools for frontend issues
4. Examine console logs and error messages
5. Test edge cases and error conditions
6. Consider performance implications of changes
7. Validate against realistic data volumes

<documentation_organization>
⚠️ DOCUMENTATION DISCIPLINE - SPEC/CURRENT/DELTA SYSTEM ⚠️

STOP DOCUMENTATION SPRAWL WITH THIS CORE SYSTEM:

1. **SPEC.md** - The Unchanging Foundation
   - Core system specifications
   - Permanent behavioral rules
   - Architectural decisions
   - API contracts
   - Versioned changes:
     - MAJOR: Breaking changes, incompatible updates
     - MINOR: New capabilities, backwards-compatible additions
     - PATCH: Clarifications, typo fixes, minor improvements

2. **CURRENT.md** - Active Project State
   - Current features and capabilities
   - Active configurations
   - Development setup
   - Common workflows
   - Updates with each release

3. **DELTA.md** - Work in Progress
   - Features under development
   - Temporary workarounds
   - Proposed changes
   - Bug fixes in progress
   - Gets merged into SPEC/CURRENT regularly

ALLOWED STANDARD FILES:
- README.md (project overview)
- LICENSE.md
- CONTRIBUTING.md
- CHANGELOG.md
- CLAUDE.md / CLAUDE.local.md (Claude Code CLI files)

DOCUMENTATION RULES:
- Use SPEC/CURRENT/DELTA for main documentation
- Archive old docs to `/archive/docs-[date]/`
- Review DELTA.md weekly
- Keep documentation DRY - no duplicates
- Consolidate scattered docs into the three-file system

AVOID SPRAWL:
- No GUIDE_v2_FINAL.md type files
- No duplicate documentation across directories
- No TODO.md, NOTES.md, IDEAS.md (use DELTA.md)
- No feature-specific .md files at root

WHEN CREATING NEW PROJECTS:
1. Start with SPEC/CURRENT/DELTA + README
2. Resist creating feature-specific .md files
3. Use DELTA.md for temporary notes
4. Consolidate regularly

IDIOT BEHAVIOR:
- Creating 15 different guide files
- Never consolidating documentation
- Duplicating specs across files
- Creating "FINAL_FINAL_v3.md" files

INTELLIGENT BEHAVIOR:
- Using the three-file system for core docs
- Regular DELTA → CURRENT/SPEC merges
- Archiving obsolete documentation
- Keeping standard files (README, etc.) minimal
</documentation_organization>

